<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-178-718  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 178 718  OV: 08 178 688.andM; </DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Feb 26 1990 v7 n8 p87(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Intelligent Environments Inc. Crystal 3.20. (Software Review) (oneof five evaluations of software-development expert systems in 'AItools for PC tackle app development.') (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Coffee, Peter; Dang, Lori; Erickson, Michelle.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Intelligent Environments Inc's $995 Crystal 3.20 is a relativelyinexpensive expert-system tool for software development.andP;  Itsdocumentation is thorough, and the user interface effectivelyhides the program's complexity.andP;  Programmers can develop Cextensions, and the software provides interface functions forASCII, Lotus 1-2-3, and dBASE files.andP;  Crystal users note that itlacks the sophisticated inference-engine andknowledge-representation capacities of its higher-end competitors,but state that it meets their needs and praise its convenient userinterface.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Intelligent Environments Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Crystal 3.20 (Program development software).andO;Topic:     Program Development ToolsArtificial IntelligenceSoftware PackagesEvaluation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Intelligent Environments Inc.andM;CRYSTAL 3.20andM;Of the products reviewed, Crystal is the only one with the feel and the priceof an end-user tool rather than a raw development system.andM;A 130-page manual, called Getting Started, covers everything frominstallation through relatively tricky issues, such as forcing a rule-basedsystem to loop, all in the context of a sample application that the userbuilds and refines.andM;A thick reference binder provides considerable additional detail.andM;On the screen, Crystal hides its complexity well, showing top-level rules ina condensed format.andP;  An Expand key lets the user delve deeper, as needed, toview the underlying rules.andM;The system's graphics are well behaved, appearing as a background behind therule-development window unless the user wants to give them the full screen.andM;Like GoldWorks II, Crystal provides interface functions that can workdirectly with dBASE, Lotus 1-2-3 and ASCII files as sources or destinationsof data.andP;  Crystal also includes a SNAPSHOT utility that can capture screensfrom other applications for use as Crystal graphics.andM;Extensions can be developed in C by following procedures clearly detailed inthe documentation.andP;  Applications can be delivered with an optional run-timefacility, priced at $250; quantity prices apply.andP;  Intelligent Environmentseven provides a nine-page manual that can be copied and distributed withstand-alone applications.andP;  The new version 3.5 reportedly adds VGA graphicssupport.andM;Intelligent Environments Inc., of Chelmsford, Mass., can be reached at (508)256-6412.andM;----------Buyers say .andP;  .  .andM;&quot;Crystal is good for small, simple applications where the knowledge beingcaptured is easy to represent in the form of 'if .andP;  .  .  then rules,&quot; saidCarl Fink, director of information technology research at Deloitte andamp; Touche,a management-consulting and accounting firm in Boston.andM;&quot;It doesn't have the sophisticated knowledge representation orinference-engine capabilities of some of the more expensive packages,&quot; henoted, adding that &quot;it does allow multiple clauses to be joined with eitheran 'and' or an 'or' connector within a single rule.&quot;andM;Crystal's set of cleverly implemented developers' tools for prototyping letsprogrammers quickly construct prototypes without the hassles of linking tomultiple packages for these capabilities, according to Fink.andM;&quot;For something in this price range, it has a good screen painter, ruledictionary and data dictionary, which, when combined, give me fasterprototyping,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;Some of the other packages generally require you tolink to a forms-generation or graphics package, a process that is slower andmore complex.andM;&quot;Crystal can be used as a prototyping tool for a variety of differentsystems, not just knowledge-based systems,&quot; he added.andM;&quot;We looked at four other PC-based packages: [First Class Expert SystemsInc.'s] 1st Class, [Information Builders Inc.'s] Level 5, [Neuron Data's]Nexpert Object and ART-IM,&quot; reported Mike Wittman, executive vice presidentat The Credit Network in Framingham, Mass., a supplier of consumer creditinformation to financial institutions.andM;Wittman said that Crystal allowed him to write subroutines to drawinformation from external databases on the network.andM;&quot;Being a credit-evaluation firm, we had to be able to get data from externaldatabases,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;Crystal does this extraordinarily well -- better thanany other package we've seen.&quot;andM;According to Wittman, the accessible user interface gives users a quick andeasy way to develop prototypes.andM;&quot;You do not have to be a programmer to use it -- you just follow the simpletutorial,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;It is a good environment in which to quickly test aconcept, and it gave us an inexpensive way to test assumptions.&quot;andM;</TEXT></DOC>